The Maclauren series of the integrand is found by:

\begin{align*}
x^{4}e^{-x^{2}} 
&= x^{4}\left(1+\left(-x^{2}\right)+\left(-x^{2}\right)^{2}/\left(2!\right)+\left(-x^{2}\right)^{3}/\left(3!\right)+\cdots\right) \\
&= x^{4}-x^{6}+x^{8}/2-x^{10}/6+\dots\end{align*}

Therefore, integrating term-by-term gives:

\begin{align*}I=\int_{0}^{1}x^{4}e^{-x^{2}}dx = 1/5-1/7+1/18-1/66+\dots\end{align*}

This confirms the given approximation, $\displaystyle a = 1/5-1/7+1/18.$

Moreover, this shows that the integral can be represented by an
alternating series in the form

\begin{align*}\sum_{n=1}^k (-1)^{n-1}a_n\end{align*}

Since the positive numbers \emph{a}\textsubscript{\emph{n}} are
evidently monotonically decreasing, the \emph{Alternating Series
Estimation Theorem} then says that an error bound of a partial sum can
be given by the next term \emph{a}\textsubscript{\emph{k}+1}. In this
case, the statement translates to the bound:

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 
|I-a|\leq1/66\end{align*}

hints:
Direct integration is not an option because the anti-derivative of
\emph{x}\textsuperscript{4}\emph{e}\textsuperscript{-\emph{x}\textsuperscript{2}}
can not be calculated.

Instead, start by writing the integrand as a series and then integrate
term-by-term. Recall that

\begin{align*}e^x = \sum_{n = 0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!}\end{align*}
